            <summary>
                <![CDATA[
                        <img src="https://mrvchaudron.github.io/profile/media/posts/1/chaudron.jpeg" alt="" />
                    <h3>Prof. Dr. Michel R. V. Chaudron</h3>
<p><span class="job-title">Full Professor <a rel="Organisation" href="https://research.tue.nl/en/organisations/engineering-of-software-intensive-systems" class="link team">Engineering of Software-Intensive Systems</a><br></span><a rel="Organisation" href="https://research.tue.nl/en/organisations/mathematics-and-computer-science" class="link organisation">Depertment of Mathematics and Computer Science</a>, </p>

                ]]>
            </summary>
        <content type="html">
            <![CDATA[
                    <img src="https://mrvchaudron.github.io/profile/media/posts/1/chaudron.jpeg" alt="" />
                <h3>Prof. Dr. Michel R. V. Chaudron</h3>
<p><span class="job-title">Full Professor <a rel="Organisation" href="https://research.tue.nl/en/organisations/engineering-of-software-intensive-systems" class="link team">Engineering of Software-Intensive Systems</a><br></span><a rel="Organisation" href="https://research.tue.nl/en/organisations/mathematics-and-computer-science" class="link organisation">Depertment of Mathematics and Computer Science</a>, </p>

<p>Currently, Michel Chaudron is the Chair of the Software Engineering and Technology group at the TU Eindhoven.</p>
<p>His focus areas are: designing and modeling of software architecture, reverse engineering of architecture models, assessing architecture-implementation conformance, software (architecture) visualisation, and teaching of software architecture design. Most recently, he is looking at the use of AI to improve software development tools.</p>
<p>He is active in the organisation of international conferences, including ICSE, MODELS, SEAA, EASE, ESEM. Also he is reviewer for many of the top journals in Software Engineering.</p>
<p>Prior to his he was a professor at the department of Computer Science and Engineering which is joint between Chalmers and Gothenburg University. He was program director of the M.Sc. program ICT in Business at Leiden University. He worked as a consultant in Transport and Traffic Telematics at CMG (now CGI) in The Hague.</p>
<p>Michel obtained his M.Sc. and Ph.D. under supervision of Prof. F.J. Peters at Leiden University. The research in these degrees included: program derivation for massively parallel computing, semantics of program refinement, process algebra/formal methods. During his M.Sc. and Ph.D he spent one year at the Programming Research Group at Oxford University (supervisor C.A.R. Hoare) and at Imperial College London (supervisor: C. Hankin).</p>
            ]]>
        </content>
